segments.text: So much for General Dean.
Your personal opinion of General Dean seems to be very high.
Absolutely.
He wrote a book, of course, just a couple of years after he came back to America, discussing his job in Moscow, and he was, in the book, very negative about the Russians.
He wrote the title, The Strange Alliance.
Yeah.
So...
He seemed to become more negative right after the end of the war.
I am convinced that, well I won't say I'm convinced, but I think General Dean feels the same way I do about the Russians.
I'm probably putting that the wrong way in respect to his rank, but I was a full colonel there and he was a very independent general.
I might say I feel the same way about the Russians that I think he does.
That's probably the best way to put it.
I don't think the hardcore communists will ever, ever change.
Maybe in 40, 50 years, maybe a couple of generations, the communist ideologies can change.
Now, a terrible war could have its consequences.
Maybe new regimes, this is almost unthinkable.
Let's say a new regime is not communist in Russia, maybe 50 years, yeah.
But in my lifetime, in your lifetime, I just don't see any really change whatsoever in
the communist ideology and the powers-to-be that will always assume power in Russia.
And I think we are always going to have the same problems in dealing with them.
I... And these are the feelings that you got after being in Moscow?
My years of experience, yeah.
And reflecting a lot, too.
I, when I immediately returned from Russia,
And I went to the Air War College for a course in 1950.
I spoke very highly of the Russians.
As a matter of fact, some of my classmates called me, teased me as being red or pink Charlie.
On the other hand, I spoke of the inevitability of a war with Russia.
I just knew it.
Inevitable, we'd be in a war with Russia.
After a few years, several years, five, six,
I began to change that opinion, and completely change where, no, it's not inevitable.
As a matter of fact, we might even be able to get along with it.
But now I've reverted back to my original.
Inevitably, there's got to be a war.
And it's funny to say it, but it's got to be a war in order to have world peace.
Somewhere or other, there's got to be a war.
Communism has got to be controlled some way or other, and I just don't see how it's possible to ever control it or stop it or eliminate it without conflict.
May not be us major, maybe the Chinese.
And you begin to see this crack.
Even the Communists don't believe a lie.
Oh, that's absolutely.
Now, there's a couple of other people in Moscow that you had relations with, and I'd like your impressions of those.
One was George Kennan.
George Kennan, from the standpoint of dating with the Russians, I never really talked to him as much as I'd say Ambassador Herman or maybe some of my colonel cohorts in the military, in the mission.
I think Kennan showed his impatience with the Russians more than, certainly
There was sort of an aura about the, or an atmosphere about the embassy and the military mission.
We were in the building right across the street from the Kremlin.
The embassy was called Esposo.
You've probably seen it.
I think the
Attach's, or whatever you call it now, the office, I think it had been moved from the old place where it used to be, right next to the International Hotel across the street from Kremlin.
I think it's a new building in Russia, Moscow.
I don't know where it is, since I was there.
But there was an aura about, to deal with the Russians is difficult.
After six months... And what did Cannon say about this?
Oh, I'm sure he felt the same way.
I don't remember him making a positive statement.
But when you'd fly the Ambassador around, Kennan would usually go, wouldn't he?
Oh no, no.
He wouldn't?
No, no, very seldom.
Gee, he'd stay there.
Yes, Kennan would stay back and be the chief then.
He'd take care of the home store while the Ambassador was gone.
And I don't remember spending a lot of time talking to him.
How did he impress you?
I don't remember thinking very much of him.
of what type of person he was.
He was just a very capable man, did his job well, and Ambassador Herman seemed satisfied with him.
I never even dreamed of him at one of these days being an ambassador level.
I don't know.
Well, I just never thought about it.
But I'm not surprised.
Look at me.
I was first lieutenant colonel, then major general.
The colonel, by the way, I mean the Navy captain was over there for a while, eventually became chief of naval operations, Admiral
It would be Sharktown.
I can't remember his name now, but he became the chief naval officer.
There's no doubt, to answer one of your questions, service of that nature definitely will enhance the career of a career military man.
There's no doubt about it.
Oh, sure.
What about Charles Boland?
Chip Boland.
Well, I knew him, Chip.
He was, to me, one of the...
one of the finest State Department men I think I've ever met, including Ambassador Herman.
Why do you say that?
He impressed me.
First place, he could speak the language very well, speak almost perfect Russian.
He impressed you as an able man.
He spoke well.
His personal appearance was impressive.
He looked to me like a diplomat.
He felt, I think, the same way about the Russians that I'm telling you I feel about the Russians.
I think at times I remember, if I recall correctly, I figured one of these days, I felt like Chip Boland, but like I did Kirk LeMay.
One of these days, this man will be an ambassador.
And I figured him out that way.
And to go back to Ken, see, I don't remember this impression of Ken.
I don't mean to show any disrespect for him, but he just didn't.
I didn't think of him as ever going to be an ambassador one of these days.
Chip Boland, definitely.
Why?
Because he just was more brilliant?
Or he was just more outgoing?
What about his personality?
Ken's personality was not near what Boland's was.
He was a harder man to know to me.
Chip Boland was very easy to talk to.
Ken, no.
Ken represented to me more of the, if you will, the starched, reserved diplomat.
Sort of British, a la British style, if you will.
I don't know what that means anything.
That's the way I look at it.
Whereas Chip Boland is the typical old easygoing American.
And I grew to be very close with Chip Bowen.
We were very close friends.
We talked about General Dean.
There was no other real key officer over there that I can.
By the way, we had a doctor with a mission.
And we never really had any medical problems over there.
Let's talk about life in the embassy, then.
How about your quarters?
Tell me about your quarters.
I and about six other officers lived in the ex-German military attach's home quarters within walking distance of the embassy and also the Kremlin.
Klebny Paliolik Street, meaning bread.
Klebny.
Charny Kleb, which is black bread in Russian.
And then I learned conversational Russian.
I studied it religiously every day.
I had an interpreter come in.
She'd teach me Russian grammar.
It's not difficult.
I'm very interested in it.
Did you get very proficient?
No.
I really didn't have a chance to.
I looked for chances to practice it.
And I'd always talk to my driver and my maids, always doing that.
But never really on a dedicated sense.
So you, and tell me about your quarters.
They were very adequate, typical European type quarters, small beds.
We had, I think eight of us lived there, and we had 11 servants, including the gardener.
So we were adequately covered.
And Lily, I don't even remember her last name, but it was always Lily to me, Latvian, was the, I'd say in her 60s, was the
head of the house.
She ran the household and bossed all the servants and me being the ranking officer of all the Army, Air Force, Navy guys living in the
and she and I would always talk.
As a result, we grew very close and she could speak good English.
And as a result, I learned to know a little bit about the Russian man of the street by talking with her.
And I'll get to a key discussion a little bit later on.
But the house was warm.
Winter was severe.
The heat was adequate.
I had a fireplace in my particular room.
I had sort of, I guess, the best room in the whole building.
It was just a huge home, typical wood construction, plaster on the outside.
What about the food?
The food was basically American-type food.
dishes now and then.
Always the main, one of the best parts of the meal would be the soup.
Many different kinds of soup, including the old beet borscht, which I just loved.
We had adequate meat.
Mostly American, shipped in from the United States?
Oh yes, oh definitely.
We ate a lot of cabbage.
As a matter of fact, there's a lot of variations I've learned ways to eat cabbage.
One of the best was a cabbage roll with sort of a hamburger meat inside.
They were terrific cooks, very dedicated people.
I learned to love all of them.
They were about four or five maids and one or two gardeners.
I didn't get to know them very well.
They were men.
And then I think it was one or two house maintenance people.
Were they all elderly?
Yeah, all of them.
All of them.
Well, one of the maids, I think her name was Massimova, I believe.
She was the youngest one.
I'd say she was in her late 20s.
I don't know much about her.
She spoke broken English.
Very courteous.
And she was usually the one waiting on us at the table.
We had normal breakfast, normal lunch, and normal dinner.
We lived comfortably, ate well, and had our liquor supplies, although sometimes we ran out of everything.
We never ran out of vodka.
We could always get vodka locally, either potato vodka or wheat vodka.
How about the telephones?
Do you think that the phones or do you think that the rooms were bugged?
I always expected any place I was, including the vehicle I was traveling in, to be bugged.
As a matter of fact, we were briefed this way.
All of us had to be very careful.
So you never had
political conversations while you were in your room with others or at the dinner table or anything like that?
Oh, we'd drop our guard at times and get to talking.
I'm sure many times we said things we shouldn't be talking about and I'm sure were picked up.

As a matter of fact, when I was over there, and you may recall this, is the time that they subsequently found a vibrating transmitter type like you find in the receiver of a telephone that was behind the
President's seal or the Ambassador's seal in the main dining, in the main ballroom of the Esposo house that across the street a Russian transmitter microwave was spotted on.
That thing was in there at that time.
We didn't know it.
Ingenious, ingenious methods of eavesdropping.
We had our security service
man that I talked to you about, I took him over to the safe and all, and we had his little, he had his own little very secure room in the building there by the, across the street from the Kremlin.
And of course we had our own debugging equipment.
Did you ever find any bugs in your quarters?
I don't recall finding any.
Could you sort of give me your typical routine for the average day when you weren't flying, but I mean, taking the Ambassador someplace?
Routine day would be get up and have breakfast.
About what time?
Oh, anywhere from 6 to 7, something like that, for the work day.
Yeah, that's what we're talking about.
And be up.
Many times I would walk to work just for the exercise, but in the inclement weather or if I had
real urgent business, I would have a chauffeur.
The chauffeur would be waiting outside.
At the entrance, at the gate entrance, were always stood two NKVD guards, Russian Army Guards.
They had them posted outside.
They stayed there 24 hours a day.
They even had their little cubby boxes to get back into, you know, every now and then.
But I'd get to work around, somewhere around, between 8 and 9.
Rather, a lot of, most of the time sort of boring duties and looking for things to do.
The Russian newspapers were Russian and the only thing really I could get out of them was looking at the pictures.
Of course, nothing compared to our newspapers, no such thing as an advertisement.
I'm talking about Pravda, TASS, that was one or two others.
I would, although it was not my duty, and I had to be very discreet about this and was told and briefed to be very discreet about it, I was not an intelligence man.
I was there to help the Russians, and therefore I'd compromise my capability if they ever started suspecting me as a typical attache that obviously had intelligence gathering as one of my functions.
There's no doubt they considered me that way.
No doubt.
Any and all of us included as intelligent general people.
They looked up on us.
The Russians are suspicious people.
They're suspicious people.
I'm talking about the hardcore people now.
No, what did you usually do in the morning?
Did you brief the ambassador?
I keep getting off the subject.
No, no.
No, I never bothered the ambassador except only when he called.
Every once in a while we'd have- Did General Dean brief you?
Sort of keep you up on top of the situation?

If I had a particular project, like I was preparing a trip to the Ambassador, I would keep General Dean briefed about the prospects of weather and maybe, you know, General Dean ought to keep the airplane at Cairo for a day or two longer to get an engine change, something like that.
Or if I...
knew some visitor, some VIP-type visitor was coming over, like the weatherman, to have some talks with his counterparts for collaboration and liaison and cooperation.
Then we'd have to make plans.
And I'd say, well, I've got the choker all lined up.
And we'd call over through the interpreter.
We always had to use an interpreter to make the appointment.
And a meeting is set up at 9 o'clock.
And sometimes, General Dean would go on some of these meetings.
I would escort him.
I'd go with him.

A specific example, General Dean and I visited the chief of, one of the, he wasn't the chief of staff, but he was one of the top men of the Russian Red Air Force, to give him, actually present to him, an Air Force bomb site.
And we'd never done this before, but we knew that he had them.
Because somewhere he'd been shot down and recovered.
So we knew they had the bomb site.
We weren't given anything they didn't have.
But we presented the general.
I can't remember his name, by the way.
He was Colonel General.
Colonel General was the one with the three star.
Very fine and very impressive man.
He's one of the few generals that I remember with, and I remember this right today.
He's one of the very few Russian generals that, and General Dean agrees with this.
We walked back from the meeting from the Kremlin, we were talking about it.
He talked freely to us after we gave him the bombsight and, you know, passing the social dimensions of the day.

We got upon the subject of cooperation between Americans and the Russians, and he talked very freely about he wished, you know, that we're very much alike, and there's no reason for us to, you know, together there's no reason we'll easily defeat Hitler, you know, and Mussolini, and he wished things could be better where it would be easier for him and us to have meetings.
The routine you'd have to go through with arranging a meeting is just, it would take maybe two or three days.
And these were people we were supposed to be talking to daily, you know, for liaison and cooperation and winning the war effort.
But the routine you'd have to go through with, well, for instance, it took us a month to get permission to go through the...
surrounding defenses of Moscow to go out and have a picnic on the banks of the Volga River.
It took a month to get permission for different kinds of people to do this.
Again, security.
But getting off the subject, getting back on your routine, that would be a typical part of my job.
I would see some pictures of Russian, new Russian airplanes.
diplomatic mail pouch which was free from inspection.
I'd send those back home and I'd do my best from a standpoint of intelligence.
I'd actually sit down and write sort of memos for the record of my impressions or maybe discussions with a particular general or when I'd meet some of the lower ranking
operational Red Air Force pilot types at the front.
Like when we visited the front at Lavoe, Poland, where the Russians were taking that city back, and I actually got to talk to some of the fighter pilots.
You know, I'd come back and make a memo for the record of my impressions of them.
Very impressive guys.
Okay, so let's then switch from your routine and let's talk about your field visits.
How many did you have during those thirteen months?
We made a visit to Leningrad.
Basically you'd work like an eight to five day, five days a week.
Oh yeah, okay.
So you made a visit up to Leningrad.
Wait, you made a visit to Leningrad and that was just before New Year's of 43 and 44.
and actually that was while it was under artillery siege from the Germans, but was never taken.
No.
And they had actual air raid, if you will, air raid alert procedures against artillery barrages, and at the time we were there we heard none of them, but we were taken to
a building at one time, and two binoculars could observe German observation posts.
It was that close to the city.
I took another trip with General Joe Cannon.
What did you think of Leningrad?
Tell me about that.
Very impressive city.
Yeah, but what did they do?
Why did they take you up on this trip to begin with?
Why did they take you out of Moscow?
Supply.
It was a supply mission to the field.
See, we had a right.
Let's say we were sending them supplies, so we felt we had a right to go out to the ports where these supplies would arrive and sort of touch base with the local people that were doing this work.
And this was primarily, I think, a Navy mission.
At one time, we wanted to go on up to Murmansk, but never got that chance to do that.
It was too difficult to arrange.
But the Visits Leningrad, we talked to some of the Navy officials.
I do remember taking a motor trip through the port area and seeing their naval facilities, but never even got out of the car.
We were oriented mostly to the arts and cultures of Leningrad, which were just fantastic, beautiful.
So they took us more or less on a tourist trip, primarily.
And of course, briefed us on the threat.
Sure, how'd it look?
It must have looked terrible after they were under siege for about three years.
That's right.
Well, actually, the best way I can describe any place we saw in Russia was bleak.
Bleak, bleak, bleak.
And everything blacked out at night.
No lights.
How'd the people look, Dave?
During this time they were eating horses.
Oh, yes, it's obvious.

Well, matter of fact, I saw, at night I looked out the hotel window and saw people dragging corpse on a sled, you know, it was winter time, frozen street, dragging corpse on a sled, probably taking to the cemetery.
Oh, they were, the rationing was very severe.
Leningrad was under siege, like you say.
And I guess that's one reason they wanted, they were glad to take us to Leningrad.
They could show us the difficulties and the horrors which Russia was confined with to, you know, to prod us on, to give us more supplies, more supplies.
They need more supplies.
And, of course, we poured, just poured the supplies into Russia.
The food, armor, you name it.
No telling how much we did.
Then I took another trip to the front, Leveaux, Poland, like I told you when I was taking this strictly tactical, very tactical trip, very interesting.
Saw the Red Army operating in the field with the Red, primarily the Red Air Force.
A couple of forward, advanced forward bases where the fighters, mostly P-63, P-39, the ones we gave, P-39 aircraft.
They were operating in quite a lot of those, and they loved the airplanes.
They loved the cannon in it.
We had a, I think it was a 20 or 30 millimeter gun, one gun right out of the nose of the P-39.
They loved that.
And they kept saying they loved the maneuverability of it.
And I never could understand that because I hated the airplane.
But what they meant was they loved the rate of climb.
It so happened that old airplane had the best rate of climb of any airplane we had in the inventory at that time.
And they liked the airplane.
And one more of them.
I think we must have given Russia about 14,000 of those airplanes.
Tell me about the conditions on the front, and how many went?
How many of you people went up there?
Well, of course, we escorted General Cannon, a visiting general from the Italian front, a tactical air commander in Italy.
He promised him a trip to the front, and this is what we were doing.
I went with him.
Did General Dean go?
No, General Dean didn't go on.
General Dean went on a Leningrad trip with me.
But I think that's the only trip I went with General Dean.
Of course, we visited shuttle bases several times down in Ukraine, but on the trip with about three or four of us, Army General, whatever the condition was, very primitive.
It was obvious they had gone out of their way to even calcify an old farm building.
with, you know, paint the walls white with council lines.
Sure.
And had some army bumps with new blankets.
Incidentally, they were United States blankets.
And being suspicious of them, I think they arranged that purposely, so that, you know, they were using that equipment.
It was comfortable, but very primitive.
Bedbugs, number one, every place.
Realized bedbugs?
Hell, yeah.
And flies, oh, I remember eating the soup.
Actually, you'd have to take your spoon and push the flies away from a part of the soup in the bowl and then get a quick soup, a spoonful, to take it without any flies.
And you didn't want to embarrass them.
And then actually making a comment to you, seeing what you were doing, oh, don't worry about it, they're not bad.
Were they eating them?
Oh, yeah.
Well, I don't know whether they were eating flies.
I know I didn't eat them.
They seem adept at getting them out of the way more so than I am.
I guess they were used to it.
The Russian commanders in the field were very impressive.
As a matter of fact, I distinctly remember on that particular trip, the Red Air Force tactical commander was not in the air.
He rode in the advanced tank of the army.
He was with the army commander.
That's where he rode in that tank, not the air.
And he commanded from that tank?
That's right.
He called in airstrikes right from the advanced tanks?
That's right.
He was right with the Army commander at all times.
Correlating the Air Force and the Army.
What was your opinion of that?
I was impressed.
As a matter of fact, you see over there at that time, and I think perhaps still so, the red

tactical the tactical air forces are under the army they're part of the army see at that time we really were too we were the united states army air corps yeah i know uh but uh i still think our uh air support philosophy is superior to theirs well let's not get into that i want to talk about this this visit now yeah and so what about tell me about some of some of the other conditions well uh
Let me finish.
So you were sleeping in bedbugs, and you were eating off trees with flies.
The food was adequate, and vodka.
They just poured the vodka to us continually.
And in a lot of cases, thank goodness, because it was sort of a dreary atmosphere.
We didn't get to see, we didn't hear guns shooting.
We didn't get to that point, but we were.
You weren't that close.
No, not at the Army front.
But we were at the air front, where the advanced support bases were.
This was strictly for air support, because General Cannon was an air support tactical air commander.
That's what they wanted to show him.
We just saw a lot of P-39s on the periphery of the field with bent propellers.
And their supply, like I said, we gave them so many and they were advancing in such mass movements that they'd bum up an airplane and just push it over the side and see they had more in reserve.
We were just pouring airplanes into them.
Everything they did in those big pushes, everything mass, mass, mass.
M-A-S-S, that was their philosophy.
and I saw rear echelons of supply and support for the Army going down the muddy roads past the air base.
I can't recall seeing a paved road in Russia outside of any city.
I have yet to see a paved road outside of any city, and I flew around over the area of Russia on an airplane.
And it was, you saw a lot of mud.
Oh, and it was, it was the
It's sort of like you see in the movies.
Bedraggled column that looked like it was intermingled with refugees, but this was all military supply.
What about the- Wagons going by horses.
Yeah.
Typical old country wagons stacked with you name it.
I'm sure some was ammunition.
I'm sure some was food, clothing, medical.
a medical wagon that reminded me of something I've seen in pictures of Civil War Red Cross.
Drawn to horses.
And it mixed with artillery drawn to horses.
But they were moving it up.
And like they always said, you know, they could see doubts in my eyes, I guess, but gee, this is the best you got.
It works.
It works.
It killed Germans.
That's how they'd respond?
Always.
It killed Germans.
And the key general, I think he was equivalent to a lieutenant general, the army commander at the front.
I remember us talking to him and mentioning, you know, our relations at Moscow.
I wish we could talk more than anything.

And I remember him saying this, and I don't even recall, of course we had Russians traveling with us, obviously members of the political gang up there, and he made the comment that, through the interpreter to I and General Cannon, oh, the further you get from Moscow, the easier it is to talk.
We have no problem.
The further you get from Moscow, the easier it is to get things done.
It reminded me of a very typical saying in America, you know,
You can't get anything done at the Pentagon, so I abhor the duty.
And I'm sure this was, in other words, here was a typical serviceman talking to another typical serviceman, and obviously you have the same problems no matter what country you're in.
The further you get away from headquarters, the easier it is.
I was shown a Sturmovik airplane.
This was their attack airplane, which we were very, very interested in in the United States at that time.

and which incidentally we never did copy until just recently, and we now have the A-10, the tank buster, which the Air Force has got, which to me is really essentially that same type of attack airplane, the Sturmwaffe.
It was armor-plated all across the front.
It was an inline engine and had bomb bays in the wings, and it was essentially a tank buster, if you will.
necessarily had an armor plate on the front.
It was primarily a ground support type airplane, a slow airplane, easy prey for a fighter to knock down, and always operating at low altitude.
Usually they escorted it with P-39s or some other type fighter, a Yak type fighter.
And the pilot
all this through an interpreter course all the time and of course this is where I really got interested in things.

I was asked questions from out of the zoo and they opened a little hatch on the top of the wing and showed me the little bomb bay and in this bomb bay which was about a foot wide and maybe three feet long running between the ribs of the wing was I guess about
Must have been eight or ten.
Looked to me like a French 75-millimeter round with three little fins, metal fins, welded on the end of it.
Now, this was a bomb, and it wasn't in Iraq.
They just laid in there, and they were all rusty, all covered with rust.
Now, this was the bomb load of that airplane.
It had two on each side.
I mean, it had a total of about maybe 30 or 40 of these.
What was your opinion of that?
Well, you can imagine.
As a matter of fact, I'm sure if I recall, I did try to restrain my appearance on my face in questioning, what in the world?
And again, you know, it killed Russians.
And I think I do remember, I think I did, well I asked, this looks like 75, and I think he did say, yes, it's 75.
We made bombs out of them.
Incidentally, while in Leningrad, I did go to a munitions factory where I saw them making bombs.
But not these things.
These were rusty.
And he told me that he'd make the dive on a target, whatever he was tacking on, and then he'd pull a
lever in the cockpit, and it opened the door on the bottom, and they just landed on the door.
When they opened the door, they just fell out.
And they would explode on impact.
And that's all they were.
But he said they killed Russians.
I mean, killed Germans.
I'll never forget that.
Not very effective.
Well, they swore by the storm of
And the German, we've learned from the Germans that it was a very effective airplane, but they lost a lot of the German fighters.
On the other hand, the Russians along that front had shot down many German aircraft.
The elite of the German fighters were oriented against our 8th and 15th Air Forces, you know, the attacks on Germany proper.
top pilots, the best of the German Air Force, was not on the Russian front.
And all air battles were never above 15,000 feet, something like that.
A lot of, there was a lot of air support for the German Army, Stuka type aircraft, which was easy targets for the Russian fighters to shoot down.
I think at that time, I believe,
I remember his name, Poprishkin.
He was the top ace of the Red Air Force.
I think he had 54 to his credit at that time.
Fifty-four.
That's fantastic.
Did you meet him?
No, I didn't.
I never did meet him in person.
But the conditions on that front were primitive.
How about the soldiers and the airmen that you saw, the pilots that you saw?
How did they look?
The...
I didn't see any actual maintenance facility.
This was probably an advanced staging base.
Actually an advanced forward attack base, really, and there were no maintenance facilities on the base.
It was just open field.
Like you'd find an open meadowland with a fence wire around it in, let's say, western Texas, with a few bum airplanes parked around the periphery.
aircraft had recovered this field and landed in the direction.
I saw no evidence at this time of even supply trucks, you know, that would rebomb and bomb them up.
It may have been very well just a recovery base where they'd land and then maybe refuel and go back to the rear supply base, but I don't remember even seeing any refueling trucks.
Did you see any aircraft?
Did planes come in?
I saw planes flying in the air, but there was never an airplane landed or recovered at that particular base where I was at the time.
How about at other bases on that front?
I didn't visit any of the other bases.
Why'd they take you here instead?
That's a good question.
It seems kind of strange that they'd take you here instead.
Any particular trip, and I remember you talking to me about your trip over there, and I think I asked you sort of a leading question.
